The paper deals with motion planning for robots and physically simulated systems, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The paper also discusses the use of random geometric graph theory, which is a common technique in control systems (cs.SY). The paper introduces new methods for achieving optimality in kinodynamic planning, which involves optimizing trajectories subject to dynamic constraints, making it relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the computational efficiency of the proposed methods, which is a common concern in machine learning (cs.LG) and computer vision (cs.CV).
